ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, six N-CDs with diverse optical and physicochemical properties were synthesized by a one-step microwave method adopting citric acid and small nitrogen molecules with similar structures (formamide, urea and semicarbazide) in H2O and NaOH solutions. Detailed characterization confirmed that the N-CDs were composed of N-doped sp2 conjugated domain carbon core and abundant substituents such as –NH2, –COOH, and –OH at the edge of the carbon core. The N-CDs can be understood as a directly linked electron donor (substituents) - acceptor (carbon core) system (D-A system). The FL emission of N-CDs belongs to the local excited state (LE state) after further analysis. Since substituents do not participate in the sp2 conjugation of the carbon core, there is a potential for intramolecular photoinduced electron transfer (PET) during photoexcitation (
                     Fig. 1

                     ). In fact, the prepared N-CDs exhibit rare pH-sensitivity to fluorescence intensity and luminous color. Under the neutral condition, N-CDs showed LE fluorescence emission and the fluorescence intensity reached the highest. While due to the effect of deprotonation and protonation in alkaline and acidic media, normal PET and abnormal PET were experienced between the surface state and the carbon core state of CDs, respectively. These two kinds of PET inhibited the FL emission of N-CDs to varying degrees, leading to fluorescence quenching of N-CDs. Hence, a novel fluorescence regulation mechanism has been proposed, which utilizes the competition between FL and PET in different acid-base environments to design and regulate the FL emission of CDs, essentially due to the charge on the surface of CDs and the change of their oxidation–reduction potential. In this work, the dual-channel specific recognition without separation and the “AND” logic gate detection requiring simultaneous activation of three conditions for Cu2+ and CPH in neutral conditions on the basis of charge control has been constructed.
